1.three ways to add CSS to HTML
*inline CSS
*internal CSS
*external CSS


1.1:inline CSS 
**CSS is written directly inside an HTML tag using the style sttribute.
**examle:
   <h1 style="color:blue; font-size: 24px;">hello world</h1>
**good for quick, one-off styles,but not ideal for large projects.

1.2:internal CSS
**CSS is placed inside a <style>block in the <head> section of the HTML file.
**example:
   <head>
     <style>
         p{
            color:red;
            font-size:18px;
           }
      </style>
    </head>

**useful when onl one HTML file needs styles.

1.3:external CSS
**CSS is written in a seperate .css file and linked using <link> in the HTML <head>.
**example:
     <link rel="stylesheet"href="styles.css">
**best for larger sites  -keeps styling separate and reusable across multiple pages.





2.css rule
  **elector — the HTML element you want to style (e.g., h1, p, .class, #id)
  **Declaration Block — curly braces { } with one or more property: value; pairs
  **This targets all <h1> elements and applies the styles
